            <div id="restofstory" class="more">
                <span id="ChapterParagraphTwo">
                    He worked with a certain client on advertisements that made him quite a bit of money. Then he started working with restaurants, in helping them design advertisements, and create illustrations. 
                    <br /><br />

                    When I was really small, I remember sitting in the middle seat of his motorcycle, and he would take me everywhere on it. 
                    <br /><br />

                    My mother was born in Hong Kong, whereas my father was born in the mainland. My mother’s father sailed boats, and always brought home food from the ocean, for my mother to cook. She was a wonderful home chef. My mother’s mother, my grandmother, would always help take care of us grandkids. She would help others sew Chinese dresses (cheongsam), and was very skilled and made a living as a seamstress. 
                    <br /><br />

                    At that time, my uncles and aunts and cousins (such as Debbie and Fanny) and us would all live under one roof, in Wanchai, Happy Valley area. When we would go to school, we would just go downstairs and buy some sticky rice to eat. My mother would also go to work. My father was drafting advertisements, creating movie posters. Life was difficult at the time because he would love to gamble, and my mother would love to play mahjong. So I wouldn’t say that life was fine, even though they were employed—because with all this gambling, life was made more difficult.
                    <br /><br />
