            <span id="ChapterParagraphTwo">
            
                Then later, I heard about the divorce, and I thought, what a pity. They were living in Oakland at the time, and each of them lived in a different level of the same apartment building. When I came to visit from Hawaii, Jim was still dead-set on gambling. One minute, Lisa would use her mouth to scold Jim, and the other minute, Lisa would invite him down to drink tea. So everytime we would go to lunch, they would come together as one. I told her, you always say he’s this and that, how come you care so much about him? But I guess that should be the case. So lunch, dinner, whatever it was, all three of us would go together. 
 
            </span>
            <span id="SEE_MORE"><a href="#" id="restofstory4-show"  onclick="showHide('restofstory4');return false;">SEE MORE</a>
            </span>

            <div id="restofstory4" class="more">
                <span id="ChapterParagraphTwo">
                    When I would come to California to visit, I would come over to the third floor to Jim’s apartment and watch television with them, listen to the radio, or just talk. And Jim, he had gotten older, and started having problems with his foot, and yet he was very self-reliant. But then Lisa would go over to his place, and help pick up his things for him, telling him not to take the bus with his foot being the way it is. But so many seniors take the bus to the casinos, because they can spend the day gambling, eating the buffets, and playing happily. And as long as you didn’t gamble so intensely, there wouldn’t be any problems. But Jim, he’s a bit more enthusiastic in his gambling, perhaps it’s in his feeling around morality or justice—he was always saying he was going to win back what he spent—all day he said he was going to make a killing. 
                    <br /><br />

                    With his old age in mind, it could be argued that it was not a terrible way to spend your time. But Lisa didn’t like to gamble; she liked to play mahjong. So, many times, when I would come to visit, we would play mahjong together, but I would resist playing such large bets. I would be willing, two by two, I’d play with them. They’d be very happy. Then she wanted to apply for a senior home for me, so we can all be close together, and be happy. 
                    <br /><br />

                    It was so odd, Lisa would say she disliked Jim, but then also take such good care of him. It was ironic. We would think, why get a divorce? It would only make sense if she really didn't like him. But her actions and behavior all pointed to how much she really cares about him. 
                </span>

